### 

<span key="26ed827baf6e489b93e3cb51b091d098"><span offset-key="26ed827baf6e489b93e3cb51b091d098:0">How do I configure the Amplify build process?</span></span>

<span key="74c4b7a06b7f40f4a6de110c0ceb8153"><span offset-key="74c4b7a06b7f40f4a6de110c0ceb8153:0">Configuration is done using a file named </span>`amplify.yml`<span offset-key="74c4b7a06b7f40f4a6de110c0ceb8153:2"> that resides in the root folder of your project. This file controls the </span></span><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amplify/latest/userguide/build-settings.html" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="7de5914996a24ca7ab87207068919c44" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-73319_259-73320-237__"><span data-key="059d1c04bdb949f5805f95fc4d4f5873"><span data-offset-key="059d1c04bdb949f5805f95fc4d4f5873:0">build settings</span></span></span></a><span key="eb22ce6eea6e4604b95d739e9aaa1b6e"><span offset-key="eb22ce6eea6e4604b95d739e9aaa1b6e:0"> for your application.</span></span>

<span key="4c2d4ad5726d4023825ca8a93f15fa91"><span offset-key="4c2d4ad5726d4023825ca8a93f15fa91:0">When you first begin using Amplify, this file is automatically created, but not stored in your repository. Instead, the file can be edited in the console, by clicking the "Build Settings" link in the menu.</span></span>

<span key="331a2d9855b749669be3840da98561ff"><span offset-key="331a2d9855b749669be3840da98561ff:0">Pro Tip: Don't edit the </span>`amplify.yml`<span offset-key="331a2d9855b749669be3840da98561ff:2"> file in the AWS console! You should download it, put it in your project root directory and commit it to Git to keep it version controlled.</span></span>

<span key="fe3e5a2a36aa43289f873753a33f9440"><span offset-key="fe3e5a2a36aa43289f873753a33f9440:0">Always make absolutely sure that you are not storing any secrets in this file!</span></span>

### 

<span key="5a0c49ead3e849abb0e4811f82093add"><span offset-key="5a0c49ead3e849abb0e4811f82093add:0">Why is my build working locally, but not in Amplify?</span></span>

<span key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4"><span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:0">If you are building a project using Node.js, your dependencies will be downloaded and stored by NPM in a </span>`node_modules`<span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:2"> folder. Dependency management is hard and sometimes NPM store dependencies that break your build. When this happens, you can delete your </span>`node_modules`<span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:4"> folder and reinstall your dependencies. When Amplify builds a project, by default, it caches your </span>`node_modules`<span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:6"> folder to speed up the build process. Unfortunately, sometimes this means that a bad dependency will be "stuck" in the </span>`node_modules`<span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:8"> folder that is being cached by Amplify. You can force Amplify to delete your </span>`node_modules`<span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:10"> folder and rebuild your project by temporarily adding a step to your build process defined by your </span>`amplify.yml`<span offset-key="8d5454a68a5c4711b9014861db0fb2e4:12"> file:</span></span>

### 

<span key="e36d4c7bc90845e2a81e7e878d0f1102"><span offset-key="e36d4c7bc90845e2a81e7e878d0f1102:0">Why is my OIDC callback route not working?</span></span>

<span key="4b8730f9a2c14dbfbf4a1fa68e183065">**tl;dr**</span>

<span key="e30e098d28fe4399b180f3c28cb31250"><span offset-key="e30e098d28fe4399b180f3c28cb31250:0">Add this rule: </span></span><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amplify/latest/userguide/redirects.html#redirects-for-single-page-web-apps-spa" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="77d08cbbe60c41f48d6fc868b155fd4f" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-73319_259-73320-237__"><span data-key="7e765ffb8e62404bb8afb117702e1e07"><span data-offset-key="7e765ffb8e62404bb8afb117702e1e07:0">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amplify/latest/userguide/redirects.html#redirects-for-single-page-web-apps-spa</span></span></span></a><span key="5a2db2257db440d8a88de5a046349ecc"><span offset-key="5a2db2257db440d8a88de5a046349ecc:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="65453d5aa9bc44fc9e91bc45ef30ebd8">**What's really happening?**</span>

<span key="2ee48a3908494298a2a6508892944b3b"><span offset-key="2ee48a3908494298a2a6508892944b3b:0">The redirect URL (usually something like </span>`[<https://myapp.com/implicit/callback>](<https://myapp.com/implicit/callback>)`<span offset-key="2ee48a3908494298a2a6508892944b3b:2">) that your OIDC identity provider sends the user back to leads to a route in your React app. Usually, there is a code passed back to your app using query parameters, like this: </span>`[<https://myapp.com/implicit/callback?code=asdlakjdoiajsdoiqwodiqmwxo>](<https://myapp.com/implicit/callback?code=asdlakjdoiajsdoiqwodiqmwxo>)`<span offset-key="2ee48a3908494298a2a6508892944b3b:4">. This code is used by the OIDC client in your app to retrieve tokens for the current user.</span></span>

<span key="78f88919a121450abd06190db41c4e19"><span offset-key="78f88919a121450abd06190db41c4e19:0">The issue seems to be that AWS Cloudfront (which serves your static SPA from an S3 bucket) considers the </span>`/implicit/callback`<span offset-key="78f88919a121450abd06190db41c4e19:2"> path to be a directory. This automatically triggers a 301 redirect to the equivalent path </span>*with*<span offset-key="78f88919a121450abd06190db41c4e19:4"> a trailing slash appended. Apparently this is a function of many CDNs in order to normalize paths to maximize cache hits. This also seems to cause lots of problems with various static websites and SPAs.</span></span>

<span key="d27bc7c50eb744eea00495303be79763"><span offset-key="d27bc7c50eb744eea00495303be79763:0">For some reason, which is not clear to me, by default Cloudfront not only does a 301 redirect, but </span>*also*<span offset-key="d27bc7c50eb744eea00495303be79763:2"> strips off query parameters... which breaks our callback. Cloudfront </span>*does*<span offset-key="d27bc7c50eb744eea00495303be79763:4"> </span></span><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/QueryStringParameters.html" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="c96db1ef3a7c4e0e9a45ed0b97854135" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-73319_259-73320-237__"><span data-key="b47b0ff4160544d787d490de9a9e085f"><span data-offset-key="b47b0ff4160544d787d490de9a9e085f:0">support</span></span></span></a><span key="7bb4ca5981f44b0e9aa5000e4f8498c3"><span offset-key="7bb4ca5981f44b0e9aa5000e4f8498c3:0"> 301 forwarding while preserving query parameters, but that option is not able to be configured using Amplify. Though, this feature does appear to be on their backlog: </span></span><a href="https://github.com/aws-amplify/amplify-console/issues/97" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="09aa0753b31b46b78d93adf5d05a729c" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-73319_259-73320-237__"><span data-key="65e3c61d21e54da695e3b6227c0c772e"><span data-offset-key="65e3c61d21e54da695e3b6227c0c772e:0">https://github.com/aws-amplify/amplify-console/issues/97</span></span></span></a><span key="2b9d313de74443a5993dbcdd23c2b79c"><span offset-key="2b9d313de74443a5993dbcdd23c2b79c:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="72f5291b5dc14da6bcec8ff81ebe5cf4"><span offset-key="72f5291b5dc14da6bcec8ff81ebe5cf4:0">For now though, you can add a rewrite rule that's specified here, which will resolve the </span></span><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amplify/latest/userguide/redirects.html#redirects-for-single-page-web-apps-spa" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="418ca57570c84e6d8f3041d584e3097b" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-73319_259-73320-237__"><span data-key="c14be0befd254ec18818aef6a9b14f91"><span data-offset-key="c14be0befd254ec18818aef6a9b14f91:0">issue</span></span></span></a><span key="ddc7bb7eefdd418cb3b16c7208a40a13"><span offset-key="ddc7bb7eefdd418cb3b16c7208a40a13:0">... though why it does is not clear.</span></span>

<span key="0b76ab42c0cd488e999dedb1f4dd29d1"><span offset-key="0b76ab42c0cd488e999dedb1f4dd29d1:0">If deploying an SPA to Amplify that does client-side authentication using OIDC w/PKCE, you'll need to following the directions here to add a rewrite rule that will allow your callback route to work properly: </span></span><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amplify/latest/userguide/redirects.html#redirects-for-single-page-web-apps-spa" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="f73a810c25d847ef86750a312711be17" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-73319_259-73320-237__"><span data-key="0d528086422b48dfa7439e532ef1c687"><span data-offset-key="0d528086422b48dfa7439e532ef1c687:0">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amplify/latest/userguide/redirects.html#redirects-for-single-page-web-apps-spa</span></span></span></a><span key="6513c89644ed455c88d4dca7591d5900"><span offset-key="6513c89644ed455c88d4dca7591d5900:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>
